{
  "texts": [
    "However, despite its strong performance, the model's reliance on pre-trained ImageNet weights and potential bias towards overrepresented species in the dataset may limit its generalizability to broader paleontological applications.",
    "Studies have explored DL for classifying trace fossils (refer to Table 4).",
    "Ha and Kim (2023) present an Xception DL architecture for the classification of large ornithopod dinosaur footprints.",
    "The core novelty of this work lies in leveraging TL by fine-tuning Xception, which was pre-trained on ImageNet (Deng et al. 2009), to adapt to the domain of ichnology (the study of trace fossils).",
    "The standard Xception architecture was modified by replacing the original fully connected layer with a custom classification head comprising two dense layers (64 and 32 nodes) followed by a softmax layer for predicting three classes: Caririchnium, Hadrosauropodus, and Iguanodontipus."
  ]
}